WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:18.110 --> 00:00:19.410
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Hello it's --

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:23.750
my name is Nancy Groce
and its June 6, 2017.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:27.700
And I'm here with Burt Feintuch
to talk about his career

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:32.860
and his experiences as a folklorist
and a scholar and a musician.

00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:35.330
And first of all thanks
so much for joining us.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:36.630
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: My pleasure.

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:38.010 position:56%
I was flattered that you invited me.

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:40.130
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Yeah, and you're
here for a Batten lecture,

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:41.440
which will be given tomorrow.

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:43.000
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Right, mm-hmm.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.790
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Talking
about New Orleans and -

00:00:45.790 --> 00:00:49.570
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: And this
idea of cultural integrity

00:00:49.570 --> 00:00:53.400 position:56%
that I've been talking about lately.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:57.590
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So I understand
that your very generously going

00:00:57.590 --> 00:01:00.100
to have some of your collections
come here to the library,

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:04.010
so we wanted to just talk to you
about how these collections came

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:09.550
to be and how you came to
be a folklorist and very -

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:12.450
kind of just an overview.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:19.570
So, do you want to start with, did
you start off to be a folklorist

00:01:19.570 --> 00:01:22.610
or a musician or where
did you grow up?

00:01:22.610 --> 00:01:25.130
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I grew up mostly
in the suburbs of Philadelphia.

00:01:25.130 --> 00:01:27.110
I grew up in Flutatown.

00:01:27.110 --> 00:01:28.410
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Flutatown.

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:29.710
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: That's
in Pennsylvania.

00:01:29.710 --> 00:01:31.010
Yeah I was born in Jersey City

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:33.940
which my mother concealed
from me for years.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:35.240
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And
what year was that?

00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:37.490
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: That was 1949.

00:01:37.490 --> 00:01:41.210 position:56%
I lived for the first several years
of my life in Rutherford, New Jersey

00:01:41.210 --> 00:01:43.590
and then my father's
business from work,

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:48.490
took him to the Philadelphia
area, and we moved.

00:01:48.490 --> 00:01:51.020
And how I became a folklorist?

00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:52.950
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Yeah.

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:55.600
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Well
I have a number of ways

00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:57.290
of answering that question.

00:01:57.290 --> 00:02:03.860
One is that I would say that when
I was 13 the mother of a friend

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:05.330
of mine took the two of us

00:02:05.330 --> 00:02:09.120
to hear the Kingston Trio
at Princeton University.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:11.900
And then retrospect and
that just fired me up.

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:13.900
In retrospect I think
it may have been more

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:17.160
that it was maybe the first
life music I'd ever encountered

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:19.650
or live music on stage
that I'd ever encountered,

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:21.630
but something really excited me.

00:02:21.630 --> 00:02:25.700
And then I think inexplicably my
mother took me to see Pete Seeger

00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:28.470
after that at the Academy
of Music in Philadelphia,

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:29.980
which really fired me up

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:33.730
and you know Bob Campbell has
written something about being taken

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:35.440
to hear Pete Seeger young

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.530
and how things were never
quite the same after that.

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:41.670
And I think that was true
for me, and so this was

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:45.360
of course during the great
folk song revival of the 60's.

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:49.960
And it meant that I got active in
the folk song club in high school

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:51.320
and all this sort of stuff.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:53.150
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Were
you a singer or -

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:55.750
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I was mostly
trying to play guitar and banjo

00:02:55.750 --> 00:02:58.280
in those days, in those days.

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:02.900
And then I went on to
college at Penn State

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.180 position:56%
where Sam Bayard was still teaching.

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:06.480
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Oh really?

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:07.780
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Samuel
Preston Bayard, yeah.

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:09.080
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So did
you study with him?

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:10.380
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I did, yeah.

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:15.160 position:56%
Three or four courses and he had
studied with George Lyman Kittredge.

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:18.970
He had published one of the
first significant collections

00:03:18.970 --> 00:03:22.030
of instrumental folk music
of fiddle and fife tunes

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:23.850
from southeastern Pennsylvania.

00:03:23.850 --> 00:03:26.140
And it was a great old character.

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:28.950
I also had a course
from Bruce Rosenberg

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:30.720
who was there very briefly.

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:33.770
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: He must
have been quite young -

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:35.900
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I
think he was quite young.

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:37.400
I never really got to know him.

00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:42.730
He was going through some personal
difficulties and was barely around.

00:03:42.730 --> 00:03:44.230
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Was
this in Harrisburg?

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:45.730
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: No,
this was in State College.

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:48.560
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Oh in
State College, oh okay.

00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:52.050
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: And I was
an American Studies major

00:03:52.050 --> 00:03:57.020
but taking all the folklore courses
I could and became dimly aware

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.680
that there was such a thing as
a graduate degree in folklore.

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.460
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: What was
Bayard like as a professor?

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:03.800
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: He
was a great character.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:05.780
He seemed like an old guy then.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.920
In retrospect I'm not
really sure how old he was,

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:12.760
but he had that kind
antiquarian feel about him.

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:15.830 position:56%
He - what I think everyone remembers

00:04:15.830 --> 00:04:19.490
about Sam Bayard is
that he used snuff.

00:04:19.490 --> 00:04:21.520
That as he snorted,
he sniffed snuff.

00:04:21.520 --> 00:04:25.360
And he had a collection
of antique snuff boxes.

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:27.380
And so he would come to
class and in the middle

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:30.510
of class he'd be dipping snuff,
or whatever the expression is;

00:04:30.510 --> 00:04:33.910
I don't know what it is when you
inhale it as opposed to tuck it in.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:37.520
But - and everybody would be
watching to see what sort of horn

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:41.610
or silver or whatever snuff box he
would pull out of his coat pocket.

00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:44.680
And when he finished teaching
there was a fine powder

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:46.660
on the floor around him.

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:49.810
And you also knew that you'd
made it in his estimation

00:04:49.810 --> 00:04:55.980
if he offered you a pinch of snuff,
which eventually he did for me.

00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:58.210
It burned like crazy,
that's what I remember.

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:02.790
But he was very much
of an era, you know?

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:07.060
I think I had some sort of
general folklore class from him

00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:09.060
where he used the croppy book,

00:05:09.060 --> 00:05:12.380
the Science of Folklore,
from the 1930's.

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:16.020
I had an I think Folk Song and
Ballad or maybe just ballad class

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:17.660
with him where we basically
worked our way

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:19.460
through the Albert Freedman book

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:22.120
with him talking about
each of the texts.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:25.520
He was also one of those
people of that generation

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:29.010
who had just this deep
knowledge of the material itself.

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:31.340
You know years later I
sent him some recordings

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.760
of some instrumental music
from the northeast of England,

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:38.500
I sent him some tune book copies
too, and he was able to talk

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:42.330
about the tune histories of all
that sort of stuff, you know?

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:44.130
He had that remarkable
kind of knowledge

00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:46.850
that I think most of
us no longer have.

00:05:46.850 --> 00:05:50.750
And he was you know,
encouraging about the idea

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:53.150
of studying folklore as well.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:57.860
I also got to know Saul Brody
in those days, who was either in

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:01.190
or had finished I guess the
graduate program at Penn.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:03.400
I guess he hadn't finished
his dissertation, which -

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:05.010
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: I think that
took a little bit longer.

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:06.730
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: That
took a while, yeah.

00:06:06.730 --> 00:06:12.260 position:56%
But I lived in a house that had been
off campus, that had been claimed

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:15.000
by people who were involved

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.240
with what was called the
Penn State Folklore Society,

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.620
but was really a folk song society
sponsoring concerts and things.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:27.280
And Saul used to come and stay
there when he was around town,

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:30.860
so learn some things about
the field from him as well.

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:33.250
Really I had no idea what
I was getting into honestly

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:38.470
between Sam's terrific but quite
old fashioned way and that sort

00:06:38.470 --> 00:06:40.040
of generalities from Saul.

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:45.070 position:56%
And in fact, sometimes these days I
tell people that I think it's likely

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:47.940
that I would have become a
musicologist if I'd known there was

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:51.060
such a field back then,
but I really didn't.

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:53.950
Because I went into the field,
you know because of a passion

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:57.450
for traditional music,
for vernacular music.

00:06:57.450 --> 00:07:00.560
And it seemed like that was
the way to go in those days,

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:02.290
I'm not sure it is anymore.

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:05.440
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So you
did an undergraduate at -

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:07.160
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: At Penn State -

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.940
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And then
where did you go next?

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:12.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: University of
Pennsylvania for my Master's and PhD

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:14.540
in folklore and folk life.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:18.570
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And so - and
who were your professors there?

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:23.190
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Those days it
was Kenny Goldstein, Don Yoder,

00:07:23.190 --> 00:07:31.050
Dan Benimos, Kenny and Dan,

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:35.940
Tris Koffin were the sort
of core of that program.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:37.540
There was a guy named Tom Burns,

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:39.570
I don't know if that name
means anything to you.

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:42.750
Tom eventually sort
of left the field.

00:07:42.750 --> 00:07:46.500
I went through that program
really quickly; you know I went

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:51.050
through from entering to
finishing my PhD in four years.

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:54.650
Barbara KG came in the year
that I was basically not there,

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:56.730
writing my dissertation,
so I never really got

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:59.230
to know her in that context.

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:01.980
I think that's who was there then.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:05.360 position:56%
I also did some course work with Ray
Birdwhistle out of the department

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.320 position:56%
and someone in anthropology as well.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:10.070
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And
what did you write on?

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:11.370
What were you studying?

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:12.670
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I
wrote a dissertation

00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:16.020
about a traditional fiddler
from southeast Pennsylvania,

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:20.350
his name was Earl Zeigler or Earl
Haffler actually, it's complicated

00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:23.740
but Pop Haffler who was known as
sort of old time fiddle circles

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:28.310
and actually had a connection to
Alan Jabber and to Henry Glassy,

00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:31.030
when Henry was state folklorist.

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:33.610
I didn't know Henry in
those days before my time,

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:39.350
he had recorded Pop Haffler for
whatever sort of work he was doing.

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:42.520
Alan had visited him either
through library or NEA

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:44.200
or something at some point.

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:46.350
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Were you
playing fiddle at this time?

00:08:46.350 --> 00:08:48.950
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I started
playing the fiddle a year or two

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:50.960
into graduate school; so yes.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:56.070
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Because you're
quite well known as a fiddler.

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:57.850
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I'm
flattered; thanks.

00:08:57.850 --> 00:09:00.240
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Yeah, and when
you were collecting from him,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:02.980
were you playing fiddle
with him or were you -

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:06.480
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: To some extent
and he was an elderly man.

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:10.390
He was a taxidermist and I
spent a year visiting him.

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:14.520 position:56%
He lived in a small town not too
far - I never lived in Philadelphia.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:18.060 position:56%
When I was in graduate school in
Philly, I lived out in Bucks County,

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:22.650 position:56%
commuted an hour, hour and a half
in because my then wife was teaching

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:24.860 position:56%
in that area and it just made sense.

00:09:24.860 --> 00:09:28.100
So I was living in a
place called Lahaska,

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:31.680
Pennsylvania between New Hope and
Doylestown, if that means anything

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.860
to you; if you know
that part of the world.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.100
And Pop Haffer lived in a town

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:38.660
about half an hour away
called Quaker Town.

00:09:38.660 --> 00:09:42.860
And it was just a great
Pennsylvania name, isn't it?

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:46.540
And he had a son who was older
than I was, who was a fiddle player

00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:52.400
as well and we had more in common
in terms of repertoire than Pop,

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:57.930 position:56%
who had become kind of an attraction
in old fiddlers picnics and things

00:09:57.930 --> 00:09:59.600
in that part of Pennsylvania.

00:09:59.600 --> 00:10:01.900
At that point there
weren't many people known

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:04.220
who could sort of fit that bill.

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:06.400
The old traditional musician.

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:08.040
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And
playing regional repertoire?

00:10:08.040 --> 00:10:09.340
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah.

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:11.820
You know it's been so long since
I've listened to any of that

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:14.680
or thought about it, I can't
really talk much about it anymore.

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:21.610
I think my interest has always been
more in sort of understanding kind

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:25.890
of why people make music and how
people make music and how it fits

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:29.440
in their lives then it
is in repertoire itself.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:32.310
So, I spent pretty much a
year visiting and interviewing

00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:34.300
and traveling around
a little bit with him.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:39.920
His wife died in that time and
he went into a deep depression

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:43.520
and stopped playing and you
know I happened to be with him

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:47.920
when he picked it up again, which
was an emotional moment for him.

00:10:47.920 --> 00:10:50.670
It was a terrific experience.

00:10:50.670 --> 00:10:54.060
It was also a dissertation
that was very much influenced

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:56.670
by all the performance theory
stuff that was happening

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:59.340
in those days for better or worse.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:02.760
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: We've
recovered from the field but -

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:05.400
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah,
but it's sort

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:08.930
of not the dissertation
I would write now.

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:11.890
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And you were also
doing some collecting in Kentucky

00:11:11.890 --> 00:11:13.690
and Tennessee early
in your career, right?

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:15.010
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: A
little bit later.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:21.100 position:56%
What happened was in the year that
I was finishing - when I was at Penn

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:25.010
which was kind of the burgeoning
periods I think for that program.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:29.210 position:56%
Although I think they kind of
fooled us in that they made us think

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:31.780
that it was a better
established program

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:34.180
and better established
discipline than it really was,

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:36.370
which I think is part of
the job they had to do.

00:11:36.370 --> 00:11:38.460
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: This would be
like in the mid to late 70's?

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:40.440
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: This
was '71 to '75.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.600
And you know the new perspective
stuff had just come out -

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:47.700
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So you were all
sure you'd have careers and -

00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:49.790
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah, in fact
they used to say that everyone

00:11:49.790 --> 00:11:54.090
who finished the degree there and
wanted an academic job got one.

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:58.690 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Penn was certainly
the leading proponent at that point.

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:01.980
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: The year that I
was finishing that didn't happen.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.530
The bottom kind of fell out
and people weren't getting jobs

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:10.400
and it was a difficult
and frustrating time.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:13.940
At the very last moment really
I learned about an opening

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:18.710
at Western Kentucky University,
which I think I learned about that

00:12:18.710 --> 00:12:22.100 position:56%
in you know April or May, very late.

00:12:22.100 --> 00:12:24.660
And it was because
Mary Clark, of Mary

00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:26.530
and Kenneth Clark, do
you know those names?

00:12:26.530 --> 00:12:27.830
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Yes.

00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:29.880
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Had announced
her retirement I think late.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:33.260
And I applied for and got that job.

