So that took me to Bowling Green,

00:12:35.690 --> 00:12:42.550
Kentucky Western Kentucky
University in the summer of 1975.

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:47.220
Where there was a great
archive of a lot

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:51.140
of old film music among
lots of other things.

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.420
Lynwood Montell had
been there for years;

00:12:53.420 --> 00:12:56.280
DK Willis had been there
before he went to UCLA.

00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:58.510
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: I'd forgotten that.

00:12:58.510 --> 00:13:01.810
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah, this was
before - DK was before my time.

00:13:01.810 --> 00:13:07.750
But there were terrific recordings
of very archaic local fiddle music

00:13:07.750 --> 00:13:12.700
that in many cases were done by
DK with Archie Green visiting.

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:18.880
Some Ed Conn and it was often, I
think Lynwood who was sort of from

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:22.980
that part of the country or not
far from that part of Kentucky.

00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:25.100
I think it was Lynwood
who led them to some

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:30.660 position:56%
of these people whom he'd known just
by virtue of having grown up there.

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:33.160
And I kind of got very
interested in that.

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:36.380
And I also early on met a fellow,

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:39.110
a wonderful fiddle player
who's become kind of legend

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:43.770
in old time fiddle revival,
a guy named Bruce Green.

00:13:43.770 --> 00:13:46.380
I don't know if that name
means anything to you?

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:50.760
Bruce was from New
Jersey, very bright guy

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:56.500
who had gotten very interested
in archaic Kentucky fiddle music

00:13:56.500 --> 00:14:01.200
and had gone to Western Kentucky
as an English major with the idea

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:05.090
that he might be able to do some
visiting and field research.

00:14:05.090 --> 00:14:11.640
And he had done a wonderful job of
sort of turning up very old players

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:14.900 position:56%
who had played a repertoire that
you just didn't hear any place else.

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:16.940
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Very
regional repertoire?

00:14:16.940 --> 00:14:18.570
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah
very regional; yeah.

00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:23.040
And it found a home recordings
and things of this sort.

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:28.220 position:56%
And was an incredibly talent, almost
mimic of some of those players

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:30.840
that he really kind of got that.

00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:33.210
You know many of us are
more kind of interpreters.

00:14:33.210 --> 00:14:36.450
He was really kind of
able to replicate things.

00:14:36.450 --> 00:14:42.100
And he used to - by that time
he had graduated, was there part

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:44.310
of the year and picking
apples in Vermont

00:14:44.310 --> 00:14:46.670
to support himself
the rest of the year.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:52.180
This really sounds like it's
certainly - but I was lucky enough

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:56.920 position:56%
that he introduced me to some of
the old time musicians that he knew.

00:14:56.920 --> 00:15:02.390
We got an early NEA folk arts grant
together to produce a double album

00:15:02.390 --> 00:15:06.000 position:56%
of both instrumental and vocal music

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.770
from that south central Kentucky
area and some of that was

00:15:10.770 --> 00:15:14.360
from the archive, and some of
that was recordings that I did

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:16.610
with the folk like
center, borrowed -

00:15:16.610 --> 00:15:20.030
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: From
the Library of Congress?

00:15:20.030 --> 00:15:21.970
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah from
the Library of Congress.

00:15:21.970 --> 00:15:28.970
And it was one of the early NEA
grants to do a sound recording.

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:32.160
Yeah and then he ended up
moving out of the area,

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:33.460
moving to North Carolina.

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:36.810
I haven't seen him for years,
but he's sort of remained kind

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:40.110
of shadow legendary
figure for that kind

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:46.150
of old repertoire,
to some extent; yeah.

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:51.480
So that's really what got me
interested in both playing

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:56.440
and learning something of the
music from that part of the world.

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:01.170
In those days western was a
master's program in folklore

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:05.410
and just getting interested
in developing strengths

00:16:05.410 --> 00:16:08.350
in the public sector, so it
was a pretty exciting time

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:10.350
to get there, to be part of that.

00:16:10.350 --> 00:16:13.250
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Can you talk a
little bit about public sector

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:15.430
because that's really when
public sector folklore started

00:16:15.430 --> 00:16:17.190
to take off, right?

00:16:17.190 --> 00:16:19.770
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Well I
guess one of the times; yeah.

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:28.340
&gt;&gt; Yeah, when I got there in '75,

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:33.510
I'm trying to remember
this, cloudy history.

00:16:33.510 --> 00:16:36.280
There was a student
- a recent graduate

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:40.130
of the program named Linda White
I think who had gotten a job

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:42.790
as I think it was State
Folklorist in Tennessee.

00:16:42.790 --> 00:16:46.940 position:56%
It was very early, before Roby
Cogswell who you would know I think.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:49.720
And there was a lot of sort
of excitement in the program

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:52.640
about the possibility of
helping students think

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:54.830
about careers in that direction.

00:16:54.830 --> 00:16:59.060
One of the first experiences I had
with student, was I think it was

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.800
in the summer when I had arrived,
before I started teaching,

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:04.150
I sat in on a master's
thesis defense

00:17:04.150 --> 00:17:07.500
by a young student named
Peggy Bulcher, for instance.

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:12.170
And of course we know
that history as well.

00:17:12.170 --> 00:17:18.280
I guess she was coming up from
Florida at that point and working;

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.170
so there were - and I also was

00:17:20.170 --> 00:17:22.870 position:56%
on the thesis committee again I
think before I even started teaching

00:17:22.870 --> 00:17:26.320
of a guy named George Reynolds
who was working for Fox Fire.

00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:31.090
So there was a little bit of,
sort of direction developing

00:17:31.090 --> 00:17:34.630
where students were getting their
masters degrees and moving off

00:17:34.630 --> 00:17:37.920
into more public or
applied kinds of work.

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:41.980
And we began talking about
what can we do to help that

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:46.150
and to encourage it and work to
develop some internships and work

00:17:46.150 --> 00:17:49.720
to develop some courses
and actually work

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:55.390
to develop what was called
historic preservation option.

00:17:55.390 --> 00:17:58.800
I think which was a non-thesis
option for the master's degree.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:01.470
We had people writing pretty
serious masters theses,

00:18:01.470 --> 00:18:03.720
but we came up with
this more courses -

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:10.240
and some of those students actually
went into historic preservation.

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:13.700
But it was also a way to
begin to move into more public

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:17.260
or applied kinds of work
through internships,

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:19.180
through their own ingenuity.

00:18:19.180 --> 00:18:27.840
And also in '85 I organized the
conference that became the book,

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:31.470
the Conservation of Culture,
which was published in '88.

00:18:31.470 --> 00:18:36.030
So that was one of the first
big public folklore conferences.

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:38.900
There'd been Bob Byington
did something

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:42.230
in Pittsburgh years earlier that
people talked about quite a lot.

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:47.290
And we did a smaller one either the
late 70's or early 80's at Western.

00:18:47.290 --> 00:18:50.680
And then '85 did one
that was quite a big one.

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:55.500
And that led, the library's
cultural conservation report

00:18:55.500 --> 00:19:02.110
that Ormond Loomis I guess had
kind of led - had been published.

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:06.650
So that there was a lot of this
conversation going on in lots

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:14.030
of places by then, but we had this
conference that had stellar line

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:17.760
up of people who are
committed to the idea of what

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:20.930
in those days was called
cultural conservation.

00:19:20.930 --> 00:19:26.130
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Are you in touch
with Max Hall NEA quite a bit?

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:29.500
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Mm-hmm, and we
had Archie there to give a keynote,

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:34.710
Archie Green came to give a
keynote and Alan Jabbour was there

00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:42.560
and that led to that book which for
a while was probably you know one

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:45.660
of the main texts for people
interested in you know reading

00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:47.620
about public folklore anyway.

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:48.920
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Did you
write it or did you -

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:50.220
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: No it was edited.

00:19:50.220 --> 00:19:54.190
It was based on that conference,
on the papers from that conference.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:57.350
I had an editor from the
University Press of Kentucky,

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:03.110 position:56%
which is one of those consortium
presses who had been sort of curious

00:20:03.110 --> 00:20:06.260
about the possibility of publishing
this, come down to the conference

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:10.010
and he left very excited
about the possibility.

00:20:10.010 --> 00:20:14.640
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: That
was really classic book;

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:17.640
it's still in print, isn't it?

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:18.940
&gt;&gt; No.

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:22.630
No, I think that there's
an online version available

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:27.010
through the Kentucky Press although
I don't actually know for sure.

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:30.850
There was a brief moment where it
looked like another press wanted

00:20:30.850 --> 00:20:36.090
to reissue it and I had the
copyright reverted to me,

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:40.160
or whatever the term is for
that and then that fell through.

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:41.970
It suddenly was one of those times

00:20:41.970 --> 00:20:44.050
when all the university
presses were saying "Oh God,

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:45.930
we're in trouble now;
what can we do"?

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:50.190
We only need to publish bestselling
fiction and cook books you know?

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:53.370
So, it never happened.

00:20:53.370 --> 00:20:55.840
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So how long
were you at Western Kentucky?

00:20:55.840 --> 00:20:57.380
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I
was there for 13 years.

00:20:57.380 --> 00:21:01.400
I was there from '75 to '88.

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:04.150
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And then
you got lured away by -

00:21:04.150 --> 00:21:09.470
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: No then I
worked hard to find another job.

00:21:09.470 --> 00:21:13.590
I - there was a lot I really
loved about being at Western.

00:21:13.590 --> 00:21:19.520
I wasn't wild about - my then wife
and I weren't wild about the idea

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:23.170
of having children grow
up there at that point.

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:28.440
And a funny way the longer
I was there the less it felt

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:31.540
like home I think too, sort
of culturally you know?

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:36.580
It was a very religiously
conservative place.

00:21:36.580 --> 00:21:40.790 position:56%
It was an hour or so from Nashville;
this is before Nashville kind

00:21:40.790 --> 00:21:42.990
of had the renaissance
that it's gone through.

00:21:42.990 --> 00:21:49.190 position:56%
It felt kind of remote and again, we
weren't so comfortable with the idea

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:51.480
of having kids grow up in a
place where they were fighting

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:53.260
about the Ten Commandments
on the wall

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:56.100
of classrooms and things
of that sort.

00:21:56.100 --> 00:22:00.440
So I actually started
looking for a job and I had -

00:22:00.440 --> 00:22:04.330
I had gotten involved with the
Kentucky Humanities Council,

00:22:04.330 --> 00:22:08.230
the state council there and in
fact had ended up chairing it

00:22:08.230 --> 00:22:11.020
in what turned out to be a
sort of challenging year.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:14.380
And our executive director
resigned to take another job.

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:16.660
And also a really rewarding year.

00:22:16.660 --> 00:22:19.980
We had an early award from
excellence from the NEH,

00:22:19.980 --> 00:22:24.950
which was then recognized in
certain councils for excellence.

00:22:24.950 --> 00:22:29.960
And as I was looking for other
kinds of jobs I started applying

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:35.030 position:56%
for humanities and directorships and
ended up in New Hampshire in '88.

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:39.410
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So you
went to New Hampshire as -

00:22:39.410 --> 00:22:42.110
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: As Director
of the Center of Humanities.

00:22:42.110 --> 00:22:45.890 position:56%
Not really as a folklorist, in fact
they weren't quite sure I think what

00:22:45.890 --> 00:22:48.750
to do with me as a folklorist.

00:22:48.750 --> 00:22:50.540
There had been someone
in the English Department

00:22:50.540 --> 00:22:54.980
who had taught a little bit
of folklore and literature

00:22:54.980 --> 00:22:58.500
but was a literary scholar
and no training in folklore

00:22:58.500 --> 00:23:01.160
or any allied field at all.

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:06.490
And there was also a name that you
probably know, Linda Morley living

00:23:06.490 --> 00:23:09.160
in Manchester, New Hampshire
who had done some work

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:11.980
as a state folklorist before
my time, was doing a little bit

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:16.300
of teaching for the University
for the English Department.

00:23:16.300 --> 00:23:20.240 position:56%
And although I've never really asked
I think what happened is some higher

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:22.420
administrator said "Okay
we're going to hire this guy,

00:23:22.420 --> 00:23:24.490
where are we going
to put a folklorist"?

00:23:24.490 --> 00:23:25.820
And they said, "Let's
put him in English"

00:23:25.820 --> 00:23:28.340
because at least the word
shows up occasionally

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:30.760
in the catalog or something there.

00:23:30.760 --> 00:23:33.790
In some ways in retrospect I think
I would have done just as well

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:35.720
or maybe better in Anthropology.

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:38.410
I mean I'm very happy in English
and my colleagues are great

00:23:38.410 --> 00:23:41.670
and they're very supportive
and interested in what I do,

00:23:41.670 --> 00:23:48.480
but really that was in a
certain sense a turning point

00:23:48.480 --> 00:23:50.170
in my career as an academic.

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:56.140 position:56%
You know I continued to write and do
the research that I do in the field,

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:58.400 position:56%
but that's not really why I'm there.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:00.280
I teach one course a year.

00:24:00.280 --> 00:24:04.920
I've been teaching, early on I
taught some folklore you know,

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:06.440
Introduction to Folklore courses

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:08.080
and I was teaching
some graduate students.

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:11.410
I eventually decided I didn't want
to teach graduate students anymore,

00:24:11.410 --> 00:24:13.080
although I taught mostly
grad students

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:15.070
at the masters level at Western.

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:19.700
Because I just didn't really enjoy
teaching English Lit grad students

00:24:19.700 --> 00:24:23.990
who wanted things from me that
I was interested in giving them.

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:25.290
And you know with my much more kind

00:24:25.290 --> 00:24:29.070
of ethnographic orientation
in that era anyhow.

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:33.040
And now in recent years I've been,
for a while I was teaching a course

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:34.580
that I called The Ethnography
of Music,

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:37.320
which was a fieldwork
class basically.

00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:40.090
And the last couple of years
I've taught an American Roots

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:41.390
music class.

00:24:41.390 --> 00:24:45.600
My classes are all cross
listed by anthropology as well.

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:49.550
But I'm really there directing
this research center, research

00:24:49.550 --> 00:24:51.750
and programming center
in the humanities.

00:24:51.750 --> 00:24:55.130
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: But in your
spare time you continue

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:57.350
to do research and fieldwork?

00:24:57.350 --> 00:24:58.650
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Sure, yeah.

00:24:58.650 --> 00:25:02.490
I love to do that and I certainly
have continued to do that.

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:04.610
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So will your
next big research project

00:25:04.610 --> 00:25:07.440
after leaving Western
Kentucky, I always think of you

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:11.070
about that time starting
to work in North Umberland,

00:25:11.070 --> 00:25:13.350
but maybe that was
a little bit later.

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:15.090
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: Yeah
actually I should tell you this,

00:25:15.090 --> 00:25:16.840
how are we doing on time?

00:25:16.840 --> 00:25:18.750
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: We're doing fine.

00:25:18.750 --> 00:25:22.340
&gt;&gt; Burt Feintuch: I should tell
you this little bit too I guess,

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:24.790
back to why I chose
to be a folklorist.

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:34.640
In 1969 in my junior year as an
undergraduate I studied abroad

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:38.300
at the University of Durham
in the Northeast of England.

00:25:38.300 --> 00:25:44.220
And it was a brand new program
then and I was vaguely aware

00:25:44.220 --> 00:25:48.690
that there was something akin to
the US folk song revival happening

00:25:48.690 --> 00:25:51.200
in the UK, but didn't
know much about it.

00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:52.590
In fact, I remember Michael Cooney,

00:25:52.590 --> 00:25:55.600
if you remember - he
told me about that.

00:25:55.600 --> 00:25:58.530
And so I got there and I
asked one of the faculty

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:00.300
where I might go hear some music.

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:03.970
And he said "Go to New Castle",
which was about 20 minutes away

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:08.810 position:56%
on the train on a Thursday night and
go to this pub called the Bridge,

00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:12.560
which turned out to be one of the
legendary clubs in the folk revival

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:18.930
in England, sort of powerful
commitment to regional music there,

00:26:18.930 --> 00:26:23.870
to local music in New Castle
as then the sort of main city

00:26:23.870 --> 00:26:25.650
of the North Umberland region,

00:26:25.650 --> 00:26:27.540
although technically
now it's not part

00:26:27.540 --> 00:26:28.860
of the county of North Umberland.

00:26:28.860 --> 00:26:34.570
It had a huge history, industrial
history and a lot of music call

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:37.820
and a lot of local song
and also a lot of -

00:26:37.820 --> 00:26:42.020
and also the whole north Umbrian
piping tradition, the small pipe,

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:45.840
a distinctive instrument from that
part of the world, to manuscripts

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:49.190
and libraries dating back
to the 1660's and so forth.

00:26:49.190 --> 00:26:53.480
And I just stumbled on
this and although had sort

00:26:53.480 --> 00:26:57.930
of split my time listening half to
the New Lost City Ramblers and half

00:26:57.930 --> 00:27:01.140
to James Brown as an undergraduate,

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:04.320
I didn't really get the idea
fully I think until I was there

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:07.370
that music is as local
as it was there.

00:27:07.370 --> 00:27:10.730
You know as people purveyed it as

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:14.950
and you know you could hear people
play a tune named for a street

00:27:14.950 --> 00:27:17.580
that you'd walk down as you went
to the train station to go back

00:27:17.580 --> 00:27:18.880
to where you were living.

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:22.340
And that really made a
