in my first summer after my
first year in graduate school.

00:54:23.870 --> 00:54:28.430
I got a grant that I
think channeled what was

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:33.440
in the Canadian folk music
society that this was a time

00:54:33.440 --> 00:54:37.270 position:56%
when Canada was thinking a lot
about multi-culturism and developing

00:54:37.270 --> 00:54:39.740
that notion of a mosaic
of cultures rather

00:54:39.740 --> 00:54:42.470
than the melting pot
metaphor we're using here.

00:54:42.470 --> 00:54:45.490
And they're interested in having
someone do some fieldwork having

00:54:45.490 --> 00:54:49.370
to do with bilingual
community in British Columbia,

00:54:49.370 --> 00:54:51.120
how that happened I
don't really know.

00:54:51.120 --> 00:54:55.530
It's where those funds came
from, why that decision was made.

00:54:55.530 --> 00:54:59.830
But I was encourage by
Kenny I think and helped

00:54:59.830 --> 00:55:01.840
in my proposal writing by Dan.

00:55:01.840 --> 00:55:05.380
Wrote a proposal, got the
grants spent this summer.

00:55:05.380 --> 00:55:09.980
I could have been just kind of
blindly looking for something to do

00:55:09.980 --> 00:55:13.980
in British Columbia
but by luck ended

00:55:13.980 --> 00:55:19.870
up in a failed finished
Utopian community on an island

00:55:19.870 --> 00:55:22.310
between the northern
part of Vancouver Island

00:55:22.310 --> 00:55:26.630
and the British Columbia
mainland, a place called Sointulla

00:55:26.630 --> 00:55:30.400
which in Finnish means harmony,
which has been established

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:35.420
around 1900, by Finnish
immigrants from Western Canada

00:55:35.420 --> 00:55:37.710
and the upper Midwest to the US.

00:55:37.710 --> 00:55:40.870
Many of whom had been
agricultural people in Finland,

00:55:40.870 --> 00:55:45.750
but ended up logging or mining and
doing things they found unpleasant.

00:55:45.750 --> 00:55:51.040
And brought over a kind of fiery
socialist leader from Finland

00:55:51.040 --> 00:55:54.210
who led them in creating a
community on this island,

00:55:54.210 --> 00:55:57.320
which for a time the Canadian
government gave to them

00:55:57.320 --> 00:56:01.040
and became kind of extra
territorial, not part of Canada.

00:56:01.040 --> 00:56:03.740
It failed as a Utopian
community in part

00:56:03.740 --> 00:56:07.530
because it wasn't suitable
for agriculture.

00:56:07.530 --> 00:56:11.830
And people went back into
mostly fishing and some logging.

00:56:11.830 --> 00:56:16.240 position:56%
But at that point, this would have
been summer of 72, 500 people living

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:22.170
in this beautiful spot in a very
kind of rugged part of Canada

00:56:22.170 --> 00:56:25.100
in those days, very
hard to get to there.

00:56:25.100 --> 00:56:31.090
And in the summer men would
go out fishing, come back in

00:56:31.090 --> 00:56:33.190
and somebody would
have a music party.

00:56:33.190 --> 00:56:37.030
And I was there recording
music and talking to people

00:56:37.030 --> 00:56:40.640
and did a little bit of writing
about that, so I have that material

00:56:40.640 --> 00:56:45.420 position:56%
as well and it was you know, an odd
thing because I don't speak Finnish.

00:56:45.420 --> 00:56:50.470
And Alli Congess Miranda did a
little bit of translation for me

00:56:50.470 --> 00:56:54.610
for something, I don't really
remember what some time after maybe

00:56:54.610 --> 00:56:57.750
as I was writing my final report
for my grant or something,

00:56:57.750 --> 00:57:01.420
but that was a marvelous
experience in beginning

00:57:01.420 --> 00:57:05.020
to understand what field work was.

00:57:05.020 --> 00:57:10.900
Again that was after a
year of graduate school.

